metadata.name: Metal Waves #24
metadata.description:
The generative arts help us to make the hardest metals and shape them to our liking. When large objects are broken into smaller pieces, flexibility increases, and the smaller the pieces, the more creative you become.
This work comprises thousend of lines made up of hundreds of points arranged in the same direction, waves made up of thousands of lines, and pieces made of dozens of waves.
Considering all the starting and ending points of these waves on the circumference of a circle is perhaps the most challenging part, In order to yield something like a round art board.

You can order a piece in any size and color if you are one of the owners. On Twitter, DM your custom size and colors. 
Made by p5.js

press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Comunidade #1
metadata.description:
Generative image from the combination of 5 layers: 1/sky, 2-4 /buildings (favelas) and hills, 5 /different elements that interact with the cityscape. Each layer has a different number of variations which could also be mirrored. The 
images are composed from original pictures of Rio de Janeiro.

Just like in the Ciudades series, in the Comunidade series the combination of the layers creates overcrowded landscapes in which the rhythm dialogues with chaos.

metadata.name: Starlings #38
metadata.description:
Come join us. 

There is safety in the flock. When predators come, we close ranks and protect each other. At night we roost together and stay warm.

In the day we swoop and soar with delight in our thousands. Still, you remain free to go off and boldly explore on your own.

Copyright 2022 Jeff Clark
--------------------------
100% generative - every bird, cloud, mountain, tree, leaf, and blade of grass.

There are 12 explicit features including different styles of landscapes, bird colors, behaviour, and orientation. Together they bring a huge variation to the outputs.

All drawing and geometric code created by Jeff Clark using standard javascript except for:

- perlin.js from https://codepen.io/sixsided/pen/emxxea.js
- tinycolor.js from https://github.com/bgrins/TinyColor

metadata.name: Type-o-Graphic #62
metadata.description:
Type-o-Graphic embraces the ethos of David Carson's groundbreaking graphic design work. It explores the intersections of typography, design, art and chance, harnessing the power of randomness to create a series of posters that are a frenetic celebration of typographic chaos.

This collection is intended to be customized and printed. Your initial thumbnail output is only the beginning — several parameters are changeable to find a combination and format to your liking. Please use the keys below to explore the thousands of possible variations within each piece.

Features:
B - Toggle border
N - Change border colour
K - Change background colour (if visible)
T - Toggle top finish (if applicable)
Up/Down - Change colour palette (43)
Left/Right - Change blend modes (20)
L - Change to Landscape
P - Change to Portrait
S - Save image

0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 - Change resolution of image
0 - 600 x 900 - (low-res)
1 - 1200 x 1800 - 4x6" @ 300dpi - (default)
2 - 2400 x 3600 - 8x12" @ 300dpi
3 - 3600 x 5400 – 12x18" @ 300dpi
4 - 4800 x 7200 - 16x24" @ 300dpi
5 - 7200 x 10800 - 24x36" @ 300dpi

See accompanying article for more info:
https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/type-o-graphic

Created with p5js by fauxjebus in 2023
Follow me on twitter or instagram @fauxjebus

metadata.name: Luminaries #25
metadata.description:
There is no light without dark.

Luminaries is a study in symmetry, contrast and flow, with a palette inspired by the twelve full moon names. Owning a Luminary enables you to request a signed print for an additional fee. 

You can learn more about features and prints at: https://www.phaust.art/luminary

Each Luminary is composed of moons in various phases. Their layout derived from a handful of geometries. They contrast with their surroundings: filled with glittering stars, inky strokes or solid colour. 

Backgrounds can split along lines of symmetry – with dark and light contrasting as strokes seamlessly flow across the two halves. 

Luminaries are alive. They’re in retrograde once a month, a day in which you’ll see yours in a new light.

------

Collection Size: 158. One for each of the confirmed moons in our solar system.

Palettes: 12 + 1. One for each of the full moons plus a rarer secret palette: Wolf, Snow, Worm, Pink, Flower, Strawberry, Buck, Sturgeon, Harvest, Hunter, Beaver, Cold, ????.

Retrograde: day of the month that your Luminary will change for one day only.

S: to save at high resolution. 

Prints: request from https://www.phaust.art/luminary

metadata.name: Sedimentary Dissolution #220
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by the geological processes related to sedimentary dissolution. Dissolution is a form of weathering which contributes to the creation of new rocks. In this piece, various algorithms take on the role of dissolution, producing visual recombinations of the original "sedimentary rock".

Instructions ::

p : save a hi-res image
e : toggle erosion on and off
s : toggle structure on and off
a : toggle all effects on and off

If offset, rgb dissolution or cross-bedding is true you can toggle it on and off.
If these features are false pressing the key will have no effect.

o : toggle offset on and off
r : toggle rgb dissolution on and off
c : toggle cross-bedding on and off

There are 20 versions you can explore, all using the same features.
Use the left and right arrow to change the random seed. 
Pressing space will re-instantiate the original random seed.

metadata.name: Stereo Print #37
metadata.description:
Generative audio painted on canvas. Tap to see and hear the composition in real time.

Stereo Print is my second collection in the paint-with-sound genre. Each mint has uniquely generated two-channel audio in the style of jazz, distortion, chimes, tones, space, or noise. The piece's visual texture is sourced directly from the audio signal. The raw waveforms are layered, masked, and transformed to produce the final composition.

Made with Web Audio and p5js. Idlebit, 2022.

metadata.name: Echoes of Enough #49
metadata.description:
"Echoes of Enough" is a collection that explores self-worth, acceptance, and validation. The collection presents a visual representation of the struggles, doubts, and triumphs of recognizing our own value. Each piece delves into different aspects of ourselves and how they contribute to this feeling.

The seemingly chaotic yet orderly arrangement of the shapes in this collection reflects the tumultuous nature of the human experience. It speaks to the push and pull of self-doubt and the struggle to acknowledge one's own worth, while the raw and unrefined nature of the collection reflects the brutal reality of the human experience.

A hidden harmony beneath the surface represents the truth that we are all enough, just as we are. The collection invites the viewer to look within and acknowledge their own struggles and triumphs and to find comfort in the realization that the feeling of being enough is always present, like an echo that lingers. 

It is a reminder that we are enough, just as we are.



The artwork is fully created in javascript with the p5js library. 
The ideal viewing resolution is 1000x1000, and the artwork can be scaled to any size/resolution. The grain effect will fade slightly for higher resolutions.
